definition.value: The study of language revolving around people identifying as gay, lesbian, bisexual, transgender, and queer (LGBTQ).
The study of language revolving around people identifying as transgender.
The jargon or language of a group, often employed to exclude or mislead people outside the group.
A secretive language form used by a subculture.
A technical terminology unique to a particular subject.
A secret language used by various groups (e.g., schoolmates, outlaws, colleagues, gay people among many others) to prevent outsiders from understanding their conversations.
An argot used specifically by people deemed criminals.
An argot used specifically by gay people.
"Gay argot" here is an umbrella category for LGBTQIA+ and other sexual and gender minority spoken argots.
Therapy that emphasizes lifelong patterns, affective change techniques, and the therapeutic relationship.
Pertaining to sexual behavior or identity which does not conform to conventional heterosexual norms, assumptions etc.

A person whose identity is female, based on societal and cultural conceptualizations of being female, usually (but not always) reflected by specific anatomical variations, chromosome combinations, and/or sex hormones.

A person whose identity is male, based on societal and cultural conceptualizations of being male, usually (but not always) reflected by specific anatomical variations, chromosome combinations, and/or sex hormones.
A cisgender man.
A man who was assigned female at birth.
Someone with a male gender identity who is attracted to those with female gender identities.

definition.value: Someone with a male gender identity who is attracted to those with male gender identities.
A man who identifies as bisexual.

label.value: man who has sex with men

definition.value: Male persons who engage in sexual activity with members of the same sex, regardless of how they identify themselves.
A transgender person with a male gender identity who is attracted to others with male gender identities.
A man who identifies as pansexual.

label.value: woman who has sex with women

definition.value: Women who engage in sexual activities with other women, whether or not they identify themselves as lesbian, bisexual, heterosexual, or dispense with sexual identification altogether.
A woman who identifies as bisexual.

Typically, someone with a female gender identity (or related gender identity) who is attracted to those with female gender identities, or attraction to those identifying within a feminine gender-area (including transfeminine persons, femme nonbinary people, nonbinary women, demigirls, etc.). May also refer to a lesbian political identity (as in a political lesbian) or a person who is lesbian-like in some quality or nature (as in a male lesbian).
Note that some persons who are nonbinary may identify as lesbian.
A woman who identifies as pansexual.
Someone with a female gender identity who is attracted to those with male gender identities.
A woman who was assigned male at birth.
Note that, because "transgender" is an adjective, "trans woman" is preferable to "transwoman".
A cisgender woman.
A transgender person with a female gender identity who is attracted to others with female gender identities.
A person who identifies as asexual.
A person who identifies as bisexual.
A cisgender/cissexual person: one whose gender matches his or her biological sex.

A person who is attracted to people of gender identities other than their own, typically used to refer to those with female gender identities who are attracted to those with male gender identities, or vice versa.
A person who identifies as pansexual.
Aversive therapy which pairs behavior with electric shocks of mild to higher intensities.

Aversive therapy by electric shock has been, mostly historically, used in attempts to painfully "convert" gay persons to heterosexuality and transgender persons to being cisgender (despite a lack of evidence of the possibility or efficacy of such a process).
Person with a transfeminine gender identity.
Person with a transmasculine gender identity.
A person either with a specific identity called nonbinary or a person who identifies as any gender falling under the nonbinary gender umbrella.
A person whose gender identity is not exclusively male or female; a person having a gender identity which is outside of the gender binary (i.e. male and female).
A woman who identifies as asexual.
A man who identifies as asexual.
A person who is attracted solely or primarily to others of the same gender (or sex, depending on precise usage), i.e. being either a male androphile or a female gynephile.

Note that transgender women who are attracted to women can be described as gay women (or lesbians; sometimes the term "transbian" is used). Equivalently, transgender men who are attracted to men can be described as gay men.
A person who identifies as genderqueer.

label.value: genderqueer, gender nonconforming, and gender nonbinary people

definition.value: Persons who are genderqueer, identify as nonbinary, or are otherwise gender nonconforming.
Persons who are transgender or gender nonconforming.
A person who considers themself to be gender nonconforming or someone who expresses gender nonconformity to some extent.
A person who does non conform to expected or enforced gender roles, identities, and/or expressions.
A person who identifies as agender.
A person who identifies as an androgyne.

Contemporarily, "androgyne" is used as a non-binary gender identity associated to variable extent with androgyny or androgynous expression. Androgynes may describe their gender as simultaneously masculine and feminine.

The origin of the term androgyne in English is multifaceted, being both a borrowing from the Latin androgynus and the French androgyne (itself derived from the Latin androgynus). The Latin form appears to have originated from the ancient Greek ᾰ̓νδρόγῠνος (andrógunos), a combination of the prefix ἀνήρ (anḗr, "man") and the suffix γυνή (gunḗ, "woman").
A person who identifies as bigender.
A person who identifies as genderfluid.
A person who identifies as demigender.
A person who identifies as neutrois.
